09/Sep/22 6:53 AM;5acffeafaa802f2a797a955c;{quote}We need to think about it, but I think overwriting the OLDEST may not be the best policy ‚Äì a bunch of mispredicts are going to be load-miss-dependent, which means a fairly common case of flushes will be flushing almost everything, in which case by replacing all of our oldest checkpoints, we will need to rewind even more in the slow manner.{quote}

I‚Äôm not really trying to come up with a complicated scheme of tracking the oldest incomplete load or something.   I would guess that statistically, most branch mispredictions are going to come from younger branches (because they‚Äôve had less time to resolve), so covering those with checkpoints would be better. Overwriting the oldest just means that we‚Äôd have to recover from the next oldest checkpoint, and eat a handful more cycles rewinding.  It‚Äôs been a few years, but I did spend some time at my last job trying to find ways to be more intelligent with the checkpoint allocation, and I couldn‚Äôt find a way to make the extra benefit meaningful (or in some cases it was just worse than the basic thing).

{quote}IIRC, a checkpoint is not that much state ‚Äì ~300 bits or so for 32*9 bits ‚Äì so the ‚Äúeasy button‚Äù may be the safest.{quote}

No, it‚Äôs quite a bit more than that.  The checkpoint contains _both_ Map Tables (2 * 32 * ~9 bits), _both_ Free Lists (2 * ~300 bits), plus a few extra small things

